"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459843","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Government is exploring a number of options to address the threat from the misuse of laser pens. This is a matter we take very seriously, particularly in light of recent events that have been reported.</p><p> </p><p>There is specific legislation prohibiting the use of laser pens against aircraft. Under the Air Navigation Order (2009), it is an offence to direct or shine any light at any aircraft in flight so as to dazzle or distract the pilot of the aircraft. Anyone found guilty of this offence could be liable to a fine, up to a maximum of £2,500.</p><p> </p><p>It is also an offence to “recklessly or negligently act in a manner to endanger an aircraft, or any person in an aircraft”. Anyone found guilty of this offence could be liable to a fine, up to 5 years imprisonment, or both.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-03-22T13:51:32.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459843/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459843/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-11","Aviation: Lasers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what measures they intend to take to discourage the inappropriate use of lasers with potentially damaging consequences for pilots and air passengers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL6944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459844","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) is in regular contact with aviation industry operators on all aspects of aviation security. The Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) oversees industry’s compliance with aviation security measures. The CAA and DfT have been in contact with the relevant operators concerning the incident on 5 March. For obvious reasons the Government does not discuss the details of such contacts.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-03-17T13:20:36.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459844/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459844/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-11","Heathrow Airport: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with owners and managers at Heathrow Airport about improved security around the perimeter fence and in relation to aircraft while they are parked on the tarmac.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL6945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459846","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-22","<p>The current UK Military Flying Training System (UKMFTS) contract with Ascent Flight Training began in 2008 and will run for 25 years. Contract duration was a key user requirement and was endorsed prior to contract signature. Previous provision of military flying training was delivered through an array of contracts with multiple providers and varying lengths. As such, these contracts cannot be directly compared to the single tri-service training system partner model employed by UKMFTS.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence has not received any representations regarding the duration of the overarching UKMFTS contract.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6947","2016-03-22T17:13:58.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459846/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459846/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-11","Military Aircraft: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the suitability of the length of the current UK Military Flying Training System (UKMFTS) contract, and how the length of that contract compares to previous contracts for the UKMFTS.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL6946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459848","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-22","<p>The current UK Military Flying Training System (UKMFTS) contract with Ascent Flight Training began in 2008 and will run for 25 years. Contract duration was a key user requirement and was endorsed prior to contract signature. Previous provision of military flying training was delivered through an array of contracts with multiple providers and varying lengths. As such, these contracts cannot be directly compared to the single tri-service training system partner model employed by UKMFTS.</p><p>The Ministry of Defence has not received any representations regarding the duration of the overarching UKMFTS contract.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6946","2016-03-22T17:13:58.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459848/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459848/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-11","Military Aircraft: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have received regarding the UK Military Flying Training System contract, in particular regarding the length of that contract.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL6947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459849","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-22","<p>The current contracted requirement is for 180 pilots and 110 rear crew to be trained as new entrants under the UK Military Flying Training System (UKMFTS).</p><p>The UKMFTS solution has been designed to meet the training requirement agreed across all front line commands. This is the same process as employed for historic provision of military flying training, where the requirement has fluctuated over time. Pre-SDSR 2010, the new entrant training requirement was for 280 pilots and 170 rear crew.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-03-22T16:33:20.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459849/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459849/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-11","Military Aircraft: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many service personnel they estimate will be trained under the UK Military Flying Training System contract, and how that number compares to previous programmes.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL6948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459850","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-22","<p>Government has established a policy framework that facilitates new nuclear build in the UK. Within that framework it is for developers to propose and deliver projects. Government's focus in relation to UK capacity and capability is to maximise UK content in the supply chain for new build. To that end Government works closely with industry to develop the skills and supply chain capability to meet the demands of the new build programme, including through bodies like the Nuclear Skills Strategy Group (NSSG) and with organisations like the Nuclear Advanced Manufacturing Centre (NAMRC), which helps UK companies win work in the civil nuclear sector.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-03-22T14:37:29.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459850/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459850/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-11","Nuclear Reactors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have a plan in place to rebuild the lost capacity in the UK to design and build civil nuclear reactors.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459852","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-18","<p>The government is working to maximise the economic and social benefits accruing to the UK local and national economies as the result of the development of all new UK nuclear power stations.</p><p> </p><p>The developers of New Nuclear Power Plants, Hinkley Point C located in Somerset, Wylfa Newydd on the Isle of Anglesey and Moorside in West Cumbria are all working towards ensuring that 60% or more is spent with UK companies</p><p> </p><p>For further proposed new build including Sizewell C in Suffolk, Oldbury in South Gloucestershire &amp; Bradwell in Essex, the Government is working with the new build developers to match or better this percentage for work placed with UK firms.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-03-18T14:18:34.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459852/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459852/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-11","Hinkley Point C Power Station","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the reply by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 10 March (HL Deb, col 1406), whether the 60 per cent of jobs guaranteed in the supply chain for Hinkley Point remain guaranteed for the third nuclear plant and beyond, with which the Chinese are fully involved.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459854","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-18","<p>Government provided a response to the Science and Technology Committee’s Nuclear Research and Development Capabilities Report in February 2012, setting out the actions that would be undertaken in response to the Committee’s recommendations. The response is attached.</p><p> </p><p>Subsequently, Government worked with both Industry and Academia to develop and publish the Nuclear Industrial Strategy and a number of supporting documents in March 2013. The strategy set out, in detail, ambitions and plans for the role of nuclear in the UK energy mix to 2050 and beyond.</p><p> </p><p>The Nuclear Industrial Strategy also set out the remit for the creation of both the Nuclear Industrial Council and the Nuclear Innovation and Research Advisory Board (NIRAB), to provide advice, assistance and coordination across the relevant parties in the nuclear landscape. A working group was also created under the umbrella of the Low Carbon Innovation Coordination Group (LCICG) to better coordinate public sector spending in this area.</p><p>In the recent Spending Review, the first since the Committee’s Report, Government announced at least £250m of funding for nuclear R&amp;D. This funding is made up of 2 components: 1) an ambitious nuclear R&amp;D programme; 2) a competition to select the best value Small Modular Reactor design for the UK.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-03-18T14:25:13.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459854/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459854/answer","GovtResponseNuclear.pdf","GovtResponseNuclear.pdf","Nuclear: 2012 Govt Resp, HoL Science & Tech Cttee","Nuclear: 2012 Govt Resp, HoL Science & Tech Cttee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459854/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-11","Nuclear Power","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any of the recommendations of the Report from the Science and Technology Committee <i>Nuclear Research and Development Capabilities</i> (3rd Report, Session 2010–12, HL Paper 221), particularly the development of a long-term strategy for nuclear energy looking beyond 2025, have been taken forward.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459855","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-21","<p>Options for the new organisations continue to be developed and assessed. We expect to announce further details later this year, once the relevant decisions have been made.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6953","2016-03-21T16:32:20.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459855/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459855/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-11","Nuclear Weapons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether an experienced commercial specialist has been appointed to act as the single sponsor for all aspects of the defence nuclear enterprise, as highlighted in Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459856","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-21","<p>Options for the new organisations continue to be developed and assessed. We expect to announce further details later this year, once the relevant decisions have been made.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6952","2016-03-21T16:32:20.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459856/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459856/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-11","Trident Submarines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the new body to deliver procurement of the successor submarines will be stood up; whether it has been decided what form the new delivery body will take, and whether the government of the US has been consulted; and whether they will establish that body via primary legislation.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/461209","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Government produces Impact Assessments that set out the impacts to business of legislation. These are published on the LEGISLATION.GOV.UK website.</p><p>The UK has one of the lightest regulatory regimes in the OECD. The Netherlands, also in the EU, has the lightest. The European Commission has already reformed its approach to regulation, reducing the number of new initiatives proposed in its annual work programmes by over 80 per cent since 2014.</p><p>As part of the UK’s settlement with the EU, the European Commission is now committed to reviewing the burden of regulation each year, looking in particular at cutting red tape for small businesses. For the first time ever, specific targets to reduce costs for businesses will be introduced in the most burdensome areas.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-24T16:25:12.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/461209/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/461209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/461209/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-11","Business: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the annual cost to UK businesses of implementing EU harmonised legislation.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","30817"
