"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459300","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>Saxton Bampfylde does not act as an “employment adviser” to the Department. When recruiting for some senior positions Ministers may choose to engage an executive search agency to ensure a strong and diverse field of candidates. A procurement exercise is undertaken to contract with a suitable executive search firm for each specific recruitment campaign.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:09:06.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459300/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459300/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Saxton Bampfylde","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for how long Saxton Bampfylde Ltd has acted as an employment adviser to his Department.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459301","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>The Department and the contracted executive search agency, Saxton Bampfylde, approached individuals to consider applying for the Pubs Code Adjudicator vacancy. This was done in accordance with standard practice.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:12:15.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459301/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459301/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department or Saxton Bampfylde Ltd approached any person to apply for the Pubs Code Adjudicator vacancy.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459302","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>No such representations were made or received.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:41:47.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459302/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459302/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations were (a) made by his Department to pub companies and (b) received from such companies on the recruitment of the Pubs Code Adjudicator.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459303","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-30","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer I gave to my hon. Friend the Member for Harrow East on 10 March, Official Report, Vol 607, Col 428.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-30T09:57:07.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459303/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459303/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many people were invited to interviews for the post of Pubs Code Adjudicator; and how many people attended such interviews.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459304","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>The following individuals formed the Interview Panel for this vacancy:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Olivia Grant – a Public Appointment Assessor appointed by the regulator – The Commissioner for Public Appointments,</li><li>Katherine Courtney – Enterprise Director from the Department of Business, Innovation and Skills, and</li><li>Lewis Shand Smith, Chief Ombudsman for Ombudsman Services, as the Independent Panel Member.</li></ul>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:14:22.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459304/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459304/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, who was on the interview panels for the recruitment of the Pubs Code Adjudicator.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459305","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>No such discussions were held.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:42:30.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459305/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459305/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions his Department had with Mr Paul Newby's employer on his contributions to the draft Pubs Code.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459306","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>The process was conducted in accordance with the Code of Practice for Ministerial Appointments to Public Bodies.</p><p>Ministers at the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills took active involvement in overseeing the recruitment process for the Pubs Code Adjudicator.</p><p>The Minister for Small Business, Industry and Enterprise met the candidates judged by the panel as appointable. In accordance with the Code of Practice, a senior representative of OCPA was present at those meetings.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:52:08.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459306/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459306/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what role Ministers played in the recruitment process for the Pubs Code Adjudicator.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459307","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>In accordance with standard departmental practice, successful candidates are subject to departmental clearance checks.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:13:43.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459307/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459307/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many applicants to the Pubs Code Adjudicator vacancy were subject to departmental clearance checks; and how many applicants did not pass those checks and for what reasons.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459308","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-22","<p>£42,000 has been allocated to advertisements on the London Underground.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s new National Living Wage is a step up for working people, so it is important workers know their rights and that employers pay the new £7.20 from April 1<sup>st</sup>. The campaign will tell people about their entitlements and is targeted at employers, and workers currently earning the National Minimum Wage.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","28906","2016-03-22T15:48:32.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459308/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459308/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459308/answer/previousversion/52033","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Written Questions: Government Responses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to answer Question 28906, tabled on 3 March 2016 by the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, on the living wage.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","30776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459309","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","We continue to work closely with the aerospace industry in Northern Ireland through the UK wide Aerospace Growth Partnership to tackle barriers to growth, boost exports and grow high value jobs. This work is integral to the Northern Ireland growth implementation strategy 'Partnering for Growth' led by Invest Northern Ireland and supported by the industry body ADS. It includes action to support industry in innovation and technology development, strengthening the competitiveness and manufacturing capability of suppliers and raising skills levels<p /><p /> <br /> The steps taken to back this work include a £1.95 billion commitment by the Government, over 13 years to 2026, for new aerospace research and development projects supported by the Aerospace Technology Institute<p /><p><br> My Department and the Northern Ireland Executive are also investing a total of almost £135 million in the development of the C Series aircraft supporting hundreds of jobs in Belfast at Bombardier Aerostructures and Engineering Services and its UK supply chain.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-16T17:55:12.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459309/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459309/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Aerospace Industry: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that the manufacturing sector in Northern Ireland is able to contribute to the UK aerospace industry.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","30756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459310","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>There have been no discussions of the types described with the Adjudicator.</p><p>BIS officials met the Adjudicator after his appointment to provide him with a high level briefing on Part 4 of the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act and some areas of the draft Pubs Code in order to familiarise him with key aspects ahead of him taking up this important role. During the course of this briefing there was a discussion of some technical aspects of the market rent option arbitration process - for example, the length of time it takes to appoint an independent expert - where the Adjudicator shared his professional insights.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:12:57.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459310/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459310/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Public Houses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with the Pubs Code Adjudicator on (a) the length of leases given to pub tenants by owners of pubs, (b) implementation of the market rent only option for pub tenants and (c) the independence of the adjudicator from pub companies.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","30726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459311","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-23","<p>Officials from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) and the Department for Education (DfE) are working together at all levels to deliver the ambitious 16+ skills reform programme, supporting me in my role as joint Minister. This programme aims to achieve the best possible outcomes for young people and adults and set high standards and promote strong qualifications. Our work is intended to ensure that people have the education, training and skills that business and employers need in order to be competitive and grow.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are our flagship policy for equipping people with the skills employers demand. For young people (aged 16-19), we want the new norm to be them considering university or an apprenticeship (or both, in the case of Degree Apprenticeships), as equally valid routes to a successful career. 2.6m apprentices have started since 2010 and we are committed to 3m starts by 2020. BIS and DfE are also supporting traineeships, which are designed to equip young people aged 16-24 with skills and experience that employers are looking for. Both apprenticeships and traineeships are joint DfE/BIS programmes that are managed through clear and collaborative joint working between both Departments and their Agencies.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s ambitious reforms to the education system raise standards in English and maths, giving people the essential literacy and numeracy skills and qualifications that we know employers seek from new recruits more than any other qualifications. Learners who did not achieve a Level 2 in English and maths by the age of 16 are now required to continue to study those subjects post-16. We have also increased the level we expect people to study in apprenticeships and in traineeships and fully fund all adults to achieve their first English and maths GCSE. In addition, we are jointly leading a programme to reform Functional Skills qualifications to ensure they are robust and credible qualifications that develop the skills that employers need.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","30764","2016-03-23T16:41:56.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459311/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459311/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Education: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what cross departmental work his Department has undertaken with the Department for Education to ensure that the needs of business are met by the education system.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","30763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459312","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-23","<p>Officials from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) and the Department for Education (DfE) are working together at all levels to deliver the ambitious 16+ skills reform programme, supporting me in my role as joint Minister. This programme aims to achieve the best possible outcomes for young people and adults and set high standards and promote strong qualifications. Our work is intended to ensure that people have the education, training and skills that business and employers need in order to be competitive and grow.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are our flagship policy for equipping people with the skills employers demand. For young people (aged 16-19), we want the new norm to be them considering university or an apprenticeship (or both, in the case of Degree Apprenticeships), as equally valid routes to a successful career. 2.6m apprentices have started since 2010 and we are committed to 3m starts by 2020. BIS and DfE are also supporting traineeships, which are designed to equip young people aged 16-24 with skills and experience that employers are looking for. Both apprenticeships and traineeships are joint DfE/BIS programmes that are managed through clear and collaborative joint working between both Departments and their Agencies.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s ambitious reforms to the education system raise standards in English and maths, giving people the essential literacy and numeracy skills and qualifications that we know employers seek from new recruits more than any other qualifications. Learners who did not achieve a Level 2 in English and maths by the age of 16 are now required to continue to study those subjects post-16. We have also increased the level we expect people to study in apprenticeships and in traineeships and fully fund all adults to achieve their first English and maths GCSE. In addition, we are jointly leading a programme to reform Functional Skills qualifications to ensure they are robust and credible qualifications that develop the skills that employers need.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","30763","2016-03-23T16:41:56.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459312/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459312/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Skilled Workers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that businesses are able to recruit employees with the required level of skills.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","30764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459313","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>Apprenticeships are paid jobs and their availability is employer demand-led, so we do not publish future forecasts. The levy will put apprenticeship funding in the hands of employers and will encourage an increase in the quality and quantity of apprenticeships in England.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-16T17:48:12.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459313/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459313/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the contribution of the Minister for Skills of 10 March 2016, what assessment he has made of the potential take-up of the apprenticeship levy by employers.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","30769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459314","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Government is committed to significantly increasing the quantity and quality of apprenticeships in England to 3 million new starts by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Overall, there has been a steady decline in the amount and quality of training undertaken by employers over the last 20 years. This has been bad for productivity.</p><p> </p><p>We need a step change to reverse these trends and secure a high quality, sustainable apprenticeship programme, which is why we are introducing a levy on larger employers.</p><p> </p><p>The introduction of the apprenticeship levy will put employers in control of funding and incentivise them to train more apprentices. Large employers can potentially get out more than they put into the levy and will therefore have greater reward if they invest significantly in training their workforce.</p><p> </p><p>We are working closely with employers on the details of the design of the apprenticeship levy in preparation for its launch in April 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-16T17:46:55.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459314/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459314/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the potential number of large employers who will require existing training expenditure as a result of the introduction of the apprenticeship levy.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","30770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459315","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>Mr Newby has not been involved in the drafting of and consultation process for the Pubs Code.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:10:43.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459315/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459315/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the nature of the contribution of Mr Paul Newby was to the drafting of and consultation process for the Pubs Code; and when those contributions were delivered.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","30732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459316","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>By 2019-20 we expect the apprenticeship levy to raise £3 billion annually. We expect to spend £2.5 billion on apprenticeships in England. This is an increase of £1 billion on the £1.5 billion committed to apprenticeships in 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>This increase in expenditure demonstrates the importance that the Government places on high quality apprenticeships in supporting employers and growth of the economy.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-16T17:44:52.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459316/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459316/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Skills of 10 March 2016, whether the £1.5 billion raised by the apprenticeship levy in England referred to will be part of the £2.5 billion for 2019-20 or additional to it.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","30771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459317","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Government requires good tax compliance behaviour in procurement. Procurement Policy Note 03/14 sets out the scope, background and detailed guidance for the policy of using the procurement process to promote tax compliance:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-policy-note-0314-promoting-tax-compliance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-policy-note-0314-promoting-tax-compliance</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-16T10:43:40.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459317/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459317/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459317/answer/previousversion/51555","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-10","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing requirements on responsible tax behaviour into government procurement policy.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","30757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459318","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-16","<p>The table below sets out information about sickness absence taken by officials in my Department relating to stress for each the last five years for which figures are currently available.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No.of Staff</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of Staff</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>% of Total Working Days Lost</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>1.3%</p></td><td><p>31%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>1.5%</p></td><td><p>38%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>1.0%</p></td><td><p>23%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>1.5%</p></td><td><p>34%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>2.0%</p></td><td><p>26%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>2.1%</p></td><td><p>20%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The Cabinet Office is committed to reducing work related absence due to stress and has a number of services in place to support members of staff suffering from occupational stress. Our Workwell community is staffed by volunteers who aim to make Cabinet Office a happy and healthy workplace through a number of interventions including a listening service for staff. We also offer a 24 hour counselling support helpline through our Employee Assistance Programme provider and advocate early referral to our occupational health service where appropriate, for advice on a number of conditions including stress and mental health.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-16T10:17:27.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459318/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459318/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459318/answer/previousversion/51556","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-10","Cabinet Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of officials of his Department took sick leave for reasons relating to stress in each of the last five years; and what proportion of total sick leave that leave was in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","30645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459319","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-15","<p>I have written to the European Commission and other Member States setting out our strong view that Member States should have full discretion over what rate of VAT they can apply to these products, and that this should be considered in the context of the Commission’s Action Plan on VAT.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-15T17:28:35.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459319/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459319/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-10","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress he has made to date on negotiating with the European institutions for permission to apply a zero-rate of VAT on women's sanitary products.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","30606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459320","Department of Health","false","2016-03-17","<p>An assessment estimating the impact of the provisions introduced by the revised Tobacco Products Directive on business, including minimum pack size requirements, was published alongside a public consultation on transposition of the Directive in summer last year. A final impact assessment, reflecting the outcome of the consultation, will be published alongside the implementing Regulations.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-17T14:18:20.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459320/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459320/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-10","Tobacco: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of (a) minimum pack-size requirements and (b) other elements of the new Tobacco Products Directive.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","30625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459321","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-15","<p>The government believes that cigarette duty achieves a balance between its two fiscal goals on tobacco; to raise revenue and to protect public health.</p><p> </p><p>In considering fiscal impacts of duties, the illicit trade is an important consideration. The government is committed to tackling illicit tobacco, which undermines health and tax policy objectives and harms legitimate business. HMRC and Border Force have an established and effective strategy for tackling tobacco fraud which has seen the illicit market reduce significantly since the strategy was first launched in 2000. This has meant that, since the introduction of the tobacco duty escalator, the size of the illicit market has continued to fall.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","30627","2016-03-15T16:29:22.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459321/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459321/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-10","Tobacco: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of when the tax optimisation for cigarettes will be reached.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","30626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459322","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-15","<p>The government believes that cigarette duty achieves a balance between its two fiscal goals on tobacco; to raise revenue and to protect public health.</p><p> </p><p>In considering fiscal impacts of duties, the illicit trade is an important consideration. The government is committed to tackling illicit tobacco, which undermines health and tax policy objectives and harms legitimate business. HMRC and Border Force have an established and effective strategy for tackling tobacco fraud which has seen the illicit market reduce significantly since the strategy was first launched in 2000. This has meant that, since the introduction of the tobacco duty escalator, the size of the illicit market has continued to fall.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","30626","2016-03-15T16:29:22.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459322/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459322/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-10","Tobacco: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect of future tobacco excise increases on the black market in tobacco products.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","30627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459323","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Action Plan is due to be published by the Commission shortly. It will be subject to the normal parliamentary scrutiny process.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-15T17:21:51.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459323/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459323/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-10","VAT: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects the European Commission to publish the VAT Action Plan; and what plans he has to respond to that plan.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","30608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459324","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-15","<p>Both Government and European Commission outturn figures for the UK’s net contribution to the EU Budget in 2014 can be found in <em>European Union Finances </em>2015 (Cm 9167), Tables 3A and 3C respectively. Since outturn figures are available there is no estimate. The difference between the two figuresis primarily due to the fact that Government figures include only receipts administered by UK Government Departments. The European Commission figures include both these receipts and also those which are paid directly to UK private sector beneficiaries such as universities and small and medium sized enterprises.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-15T17:20:57.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459324/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459324/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-10","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) Government's net contribution to EU institutions and (b) UK's current account balance with those institutions in 2014; and what estimate the European Commission has made of that contribution and that account balance.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","30622"
