"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459402","Department of Health","false","2016-03-17","<p>The Short and Long Term (SALT) Care data collection for 2014-15 show the number of cared-for people receiving respite or other forms of carer support;</p><p> </p><p>(a) England – 55,735</p><p>(b) Birmingham local authority area – 635</p><p>(c) Swindon local authority area – 160</p><p> </p><p>The data include other forms of support as well as emergency respite places; a precise figure for emergency respite places is not available. We are working with councils to improve data in this area for future iterations of the SALT Care data collection.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises the invaluable contribution made by unpaid carers and the importance of supporting them in their caring roles. That is why we continue to support implementation of the improved rights for carers enshrined in the Care Act 2014. This includes a right to an assessment on the appearance of needs for support. These assessments cover carers’ wellbeing and what support they may need in their caring role.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has provided £104 million of funding to local authorities for these improved carers’ rights in 2015/16. We have also made an additional £400 million available to the National Health Service between 2011 and 2015 to provide carers with breaks from their caring responsibilities to sustain them in their caring role. The equivalent annual allocation of £130 million for carers breaks is now included in the Better Care Fund.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also leading the development of a new cross-Government National Carers Strategy that will look at what more we can do to support existing carers and future carers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","30779","2016-03-17T15:19:36.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459402/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459402/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-10","Respite Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of emergency respite places for people being cared for by family or friends in (a) England, (b) Birmingham and (c) Swindon.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","30778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459403","Department of Health","false","2016-03-17","<p>The Short and Long Term (SALT) Care data collection for 2014-15 show the number of cared-for people receiving respite or other forms of carer support;</p><p> </p><p>(a) England – 55,735</p><p>(b) Birmingham local authority area – 635</p><p>(c) Swindon local authority area – 160</p><p> </p><p>The data include other forms of support as well as emergency respite places; a precise figure for emergency respite places is not available. We are working with councils to improve data in this area for future iterations of the SALT Care data collection.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises the invaluable contribution made by unpaid carers and the importance of supporting them in their caring roles. That is why we continue to support implementation of the improved rights for carers enshrined in the Care Act 2014. This includes a right to an assessment on the appearance of needs for support. These assessments cover carers’ wellbeing and what support they may need in their caring role.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has provided £104 million of funding to local authorities for these improved carers’ rights in 2015/16. We have also made an additional £400 million available to the National Health Service between 2011 and 2015 to provide carers with breaks from their caring responsibilities to sustain them in their caring role. The equivalent annual allocation of £130 million for carers breaks is now included in the Better Care Fund.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also leading the development of a new cross-Government National Carers Strategy that will look at what more we can do to support existing carers and future carers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","30778","2016-03-17T15:19:36.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459403/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459403/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-10","Respite Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to increase the availability of respite care and support for family carers.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","30779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459404","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>The information requested is not available. Spend on research funded directly by the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) is categorised by Health Research Classification System (HRCS) health categories. There is no HRCS category for stem cell research.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to the establishment of the NIHR in April 2006, the main part of the Department’s total health research expenditure was devolved to and managed by National Health Service organisations. The NHS organisations reported on their use of these allocations in annual research and development reports. These reports estimated total, aggregated spend on certain priority areas but spend on stem cell research was not estimated. From April 2006 to March 2009, transitional research funding was allocated to these organisations at reducing levels. At the same time, an increasing amount of NHS research funding was awarded competitively through new NIHR programmes and schemes.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-03-15T12:23:14.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459404/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459404/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-10","Stem Cells: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 3 March 2016 to Question 28970, how much public funding for stem cell research has been allocated through the National Institute for Health Research in each year since 2003-04.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","30710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459405","Department of Health","false","2016-03-17","<p>NHS England has advised that three of those five services are now compliant. Two services, Birmingham Children’s Hospital NHS Foundation Trust Paediatric Bone Marrow Transplant service and Ipswich Hospital NHS Trust Bone Marrow Transplant, are still awaiting accreditation confirmation from the Joint Accreditation Committee International Society for Cellular Therapy &amp; European Group for Blood and Marrow Transplantation (JACIE). Confirmation of compliance is expected no later than December 2016 in line with the JACIE assessment programme. In the meantime, commissioners have been assured that the services are safe to continue to treat patients.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-17T14:15:27.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459405/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459405/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-10","Stem Cells: Transplant Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 8 March 2016 to Question 28967, on stem cells: transplant surgery, which five transplant centres were found to be non-compliant with the NHS England specification.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","30711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459406","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>The 2014 Adult Psychiatric Morbidity Survey is currently scheduled to be published by the Health and Social Care Information Centre in September 2016.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-15T16:20:58.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459406/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459406/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-10","Mental Illness: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects the 2014 Adult Psychiatric Morbidity Survey to be published.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","30670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459407","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>Information on the number and the proportion of women who access mental health services having experienced sexual or domestic abuse is not held centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-15T16:26:06.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459407/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459407/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-10","Mental Health Services: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of women accessing mental health services experienced sexual or domestic abuse in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","30671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459408","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>There is no general data collection collected by the health services on the numbers of children and adults who have experienced sexual abuse or physical abuse.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Specific data collections for the purposes of prevention and targeting support are published by the Health and Social Care Information Centre.</p><p> </p><p>The Safeguarding Adults Collection reported annually by the Health and Social Care Information Centre focuses on adults at risk of abuse for whom safeguarding concerns are raised with local councils which instigate investigations under the local safeguarding procedures. The data includes referrals for physical or sexual abuse. The most recent report, published in October 2015, can be viewed at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB18869/sar-1415-rep.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.hscic.gov.uk/catalogue/PUB18869/sar-1415-rep.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Crime Survey for England and Wales includes data on sexual abuse of adults aged 16 to 59 years old:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/compendium/focusonviolentcrimeandsexualoffences/yearendingmarch2015" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/compendium/focusonviolentcrimeandsexualoffences/yearendingmarch2015</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-15T17:39:42.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459408/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459408/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-10","Domestic Abuse and Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) children and (b) adults of each gender have experienced (a) sexual and (b) physical abuse in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","30672"
