"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459443","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer of 3rd March 2016, UIN 28574,</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=28574" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=28574</a>.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-15T15:44:44.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459443/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459443/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Public Transport: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Government plans to bring forward legislative proposals to implement the installation and use of audio-visual displays on public transport vehicles.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John Mc Nally","30653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459444","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>The British Transport Police does not own any of its properties, hence it has no plans to sell any of them.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-17T15:20:26.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459444/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459444/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","British Transport Police: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans there are to sell property of the British Transport Police.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","30633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459445","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>Only the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency directly employs security guards, employing 54 full time and part time security guards at a total salary cost of £868,475. All other security guards in the Department for Transport are employed and managed under outsourced contracts; pay data in such situations is not held by the Department.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-17T15:23:53.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459445/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459445/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Department for Transport: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much security guards in his Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459446","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>The provisions mentioned have been redacted at the request of either the Director General for Rail or the Secretary of State in accordance with the provisions of the Freedom of Information Act 2000.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-17T15:14:10.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459446/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459446/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","London, Tilbury and Southend Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what commercial sensitivity applies to section 106 (staff using handheld tablets) and section 28.1 (movement of staff) of the agreement between NXET Trains Limited and his Department of 15 July 2014 regarding the Essex Thameside franchise.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","30602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459447","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>The agreement between NXET Trains Limited and the Department for Transport is in the public domain and can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/486697/essex-thameside.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/486697/essex-thameside.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-17T15:17:30.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459447/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459447/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","London, Tilbury and Southend Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether there is any provision in the agreement between NXET Trains Limited and his Department of 15 July 2014 on the Essex Thameside franchise relating to the closure of ticket offices.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","30603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459448","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>Where text has been omitted from the document, this is because the Director General Rail or Secretary of State has decided to exclude the text in accordance with the provisions within the Freedom of Information Act 2000.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-15T16:28:03.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459448/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459448/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","London, Tilbury and Southend Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reason a number of the Committed Obligations agreed between NXET Trains Limited and his Department on 15 July 2014 regarding the Essex Thameside franchise are redacted in the published version of the agreement.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","30605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459449","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-18","<p>Highways England’s forthcoming work on the next iteration of their Route Strategies is the means of assessing pressures and needs and generating proposals across the entire strategic road network, including the M54 and A5. The Route Strategies will inform the preparation of the next Road Investment Strategy. Any specific proposals that require investment will of course need to be underpinned by a strong and clear business case.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-18T11:39:32.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459449/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459449/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","M54: Shrewsbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will commission a cost-benefit analysis on the potential benefit of extending the M54 to Shrewsbury on Shrewsbury and the surrounding area.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","30782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459450","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Government fully understands how important it is to have a safe road network for all road users, which is why we are providing a record £6 billion for local highways maintenance in England (outside London).</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-15T16:00:58.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459450/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459450/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Roads: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent steps he has taken to improve roads to ensure that they are safe for both motorists and cyclists.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","30755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459451","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-18","<p>The Budget 2016 document set out that a total of £2.86bn would be provided to the places that had agreed devolution deals as unringfenced single pots. This includes the consolidated transport grants. A detailed breakdown of the grant for Greater Manchester will be set out by Ministers shortly.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-18T12:35:08.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459451/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459451/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Transport: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the consolidated local transport budget for Greater Manchester after implementation of the devolution deal (a) in total and (b) per capita.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Mr David Crausby","30724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459452","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-17","<p>Transport for London (TfL) receives its funding from a wide range of sources, with the largest single contribution (around £4.6 billion in 2015/16) coming from fare-payers. This Department pays a transport grant to TfL, via the Greater London Authority, which was £1.516 billion in 2015/2016 and which will be £1.418 billion in 2016/17. We do not routinely publish a per capita breakdown of this grant, because spending on London’s transport infrastructure benefits not only London residents but also commuters and others travelling into the capital. There are also differences in the funding and regulatory framework between London and the rest of the country, making like-for-like comparisons difficult.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-17T14:59:11.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459452/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459452/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Transport: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) total and (b) per capita consolidated local transport budget for London is for (i) 2015-16 and (ii) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Mr David Crausby","30725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459453","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-16","<p>In the five financial years from 2010/11 to 2014/15, the Department for Transport has provided: £63m to Cycling England, £94m to the Cycle Ambition Cities and National Parks fund, £30m to the Linking Communities/Cycle Rail fund, £12m to Links to Schools, £44m to Bikeability cycle training and £35m to the Cycle Safety fund. Between 2011 and 2015, the Local Sustainable Transport Fund (LSTF) also provided 28% of its budget, or £151m, to cycling projects. Overall between 2011 and 2015 funding was more than doubled compared to the previous administration.</p><p> </p><p>For 2015/16, a further £15m will be invested in Cycle Rail, £11m in Bikeability and £64.5m in LSTF projects; £15m was also invested in the second phase of the Cycle Ambition City programme. Looking forward, a further £99m will be invested in the Cycle Ambition Cities, £50m in Bikeability and £100m via the Road Investment Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>Long-term funding is also available for cycling from the Integrated Transport Block, Highways Maintenance Block, and the Local Growth Fund, where around £270m is already planned by Local Enterprise Partnerships for cycling infrastructure.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-16T10:59:24.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459453/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459453/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Cycling: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding the Government has allocated to cycling schemes in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459454","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold information on Network Rail’s plans for funding towards the cost of an accessible footbridge at Bingham station.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-15T15:07:41.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459454/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459454/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Bingham Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information he holds on whether Network Rail plans to release a contribution to the cost of a disabled access footbridge at Bingham railway station in Nottinghamshire.","false","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","Newark","Robert Jenrick","30767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459455","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Cross Government Working Group on Drones is an ongoing policy group that meets quarterly to discuss a range of cross-cutting departmental issues relating to drones.</p><p> </p><p>My department is working with the European Aviation Safety Agency on the development of new European rules for drones. The Civil Aviation Authority are planning to consult on these proposals in the summer, with a view to making amendments to the Air Navigation Order in 2017.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-15T16:04:23.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459455/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459455/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the Cross Government Working Group on Drones to finish its work; and when he plans to bring forward legislative proposals.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","30772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459456","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Cross Government Working Group is undertaking analysis of the potential use of drones for criminal and terrorist purposes, and the impacts of their negligent use near sensitive locations, such as airports.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on tackling the risks of criminal drone use has been provided to constabularies across the UK.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-15T16:09:56.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459456/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459456/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Cross Government Working Group on Drones will conduct a detailed examination of the security threats posed by drones as part of its work.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","30773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459457","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>I refer the Honourable member to my answer give on 4 March, UIN 29244, <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=29244" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=29244</a>.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-15T16:24:15.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459457/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459457/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Cross Government Working Group on Drones will examine the feasibility of introducing a system of registration for drones, including an element of mandatory training and evaluation for the larger classes.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","30774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459458","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>I would like to assure the hon. Member that we are committed to improving accessibility at railway stations. However, many stations date from a time when the needs of disabled customers were simply not considered and at present only around 460 of our 2,500 stations have step free access to every platform. We have therefore continued with the Access for All programme, launched in 2006, which by 2019 will have provided step free access at more than 200 stations and has already delivered smaller scale access improvements at over 1200 stations.</p><p> </p><p>In 2013 we asked the industry to nominate stations for the latest tranche of Access for All funding. 278 were put forward and we selected 68 of these to add to the programme. To ensure the best possible value for money, these were chosen based on their annual footfall, weighted by the incidence of disability in the area. We also took into account the priorities of the industry and other factors such as the availability of third party funding. Around a third were also chosen to ensure a fair geographical spread across the country.</p><p> </p><p>Bingham was not among the 278 stations nominated.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-15T15:13:07.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459458/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459458/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-10","Bingham Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to ensure disabled access on all platforms at Bingham railway station.","false","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","Newark","Robert Jenrick","30775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459459","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-18","<p>DWP do not directly employ any security guards, they are supplied via our PFI contractor Telereal Trillium who subcontract the supply of all security to G4S.</p><p> </p><p>G4S pay rates (as of 1 January 2016) vary on geographical location and the average pay rate for each Government Office Region (GOR) is set out below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>GOVERNMENT OFFICE REGION</p></td><td><p>HOURLY PAY RATE (Average)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 1 Scotland</p></td><td><p>£7.84</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 2 North East</p></td><td><p>£7.84</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 3 North West</p></td><td><p>£7.85</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 4 Yorkshire &amp; Humberside</p></td><td><p>£7.86</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 5 East Midlands</p></td><td><p>£7.86</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 6 West Midlands</p></td><td><p>£7.83</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 7 East of England</p></td><td><p>£8.38</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 8 Wales</p></td><td><p>£7.87</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 9 Southern</p></td><td><p>£8.39</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 10 London</p></td><td><p>£9.26</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>GOR 11 South West</p></td><td><p>£7.88</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>All G4S security guards/officers (irrespective of age) are already paid above the National Living Wage of £7.20/hour which will be introduced from 01-Apr-16.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-18T13:38:20.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459459/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459459/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-10","Department for Work and Pensions: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much security guards in his Department are paid.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","30613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459460","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-18","<p>Child Maintenance Options provide free and impartial information and support to help separated parents make decisions about their child maintenance arrangements. For parents who are unable to make a family-based arrangement the government has introduced a new statutory Child Maintenance Service, which will bring speedier processing of applications, simpler calculations and faster enforcement action, where necessary.</p><p>Where parents fail to fulfil their financial responsibilities towards their children we have a range of strong enforcement powers at our disposal. These powers include deducting maintenance directly from earnings, instructing bailiffs to collect arrears or seize goods, forcing the sale of property, disqualification from driving and commitment to prison.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-18T13:29:01.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459460/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459460/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-10","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that absent parents financially support their children.","false","Biography information for Gordon Henderson","Sittingbourne and Sheppey","Gordon Henderson","30635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459461","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-15","<p>In accordance with government policy in this area, the Department does not publish risk registers for major programmes.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-15T15:32:29.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459461/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459461/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-10","Universal Credit: Risk Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish the risk register for the universal credit programme.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","30624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459462","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-17","<p>The Shared Parental Leave and Pay system is designed to strike the right balance between giving employees flexibility and giving their employers the certainty that they need to plan.</p><p>We do not routinely collect information that would enable us to estimate the proportion of (a) mothers and (b) fathers in the labour force who were not able to claim Shared Parental Leave and Pay because of the ‘continuity of employment requirement’.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-17T16:24:32.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459462/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/459462/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-10","Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate the proportion of (a) mothers and (b) fathers in the labour force who were not able to claim statutory parental leave because of the requirement for 26 weeks of continuous employment with the same employer in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","30632"
