"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458850","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>London’s cycle superhighways are a matter for the Mayor and Transport for London and the Department has not made any assessment of their impact on the number of cyclists.</p><p> </p><p>In his press release of 19 November 2015, the Mayor stated that there had been a 29% increase in the total number of cyclists crossing Vauxhall Bridge in the busiest peak hour since the opening of the superhighway from Oval to Pimlico.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-03-15T13:04:51.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458850/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458850/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Cycleways: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the London Cycle superhighways on the number of cyclists.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL6884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458851","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-15","<p>London’s cycle superhighways are a matter for the Mayor and Transport for London (TfL) and the Department has not made any assessment of the impact of their construction on the journey times of buses.</p><p> </p><p>At any time, different bus routes may be affected by delays and/or diversions as a result of construction works related to the cycle superhighway or other factors and TfL regularly updates the travel information on their website to reflect these changes.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-03-15T13:05:12.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458851/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458851/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-09","Cycleways: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the London Cycle superhighways on the journey times of buses whose routes run parallel to or intersect with the highways.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL6885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458852","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-21","<p>In October 2015 the Government announced that, by the end of this Parliament, local authorities will be able to keep 100 per cent of the business rates they raise locally. The Department for Communities and Local Government and the Local Government Association will work with local authorities, businesses and other interested parties in the intervening period to develop proposals. There will be continued opportunity for the sector and the public to engage with the reforms.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-03-21T15:40:33.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458852/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458852/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Local Government Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 7 March (HL6264), whether they will specify timelines for reviewing the formula that assesses a local authority’s needs against the costs that it incurs in addressing those needs, including when that review will start, when that consultation will be announced, how long the consultation period will be, when they expect that review to conclude, and when the outcomes of that review will be announced.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL6886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458853","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-17","<p>The F-35B Lightning II aircraft and its Autonomic Logistics Information System (ALIS) have both been designed to be resilient against cyber attack and will be the subject of testing throughout the life of the programme.</p><p>Risk assessments of the aircraft and ALIS vulnerability to cyber attacks are conducted continuously. In addition, all classified data transmission to and from the F-35B Lightning II aircraft is fully encrypted.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-03-17T17:18:16.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458853/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458853/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what testing has been done on software systems for UK F-35 Lightning II fighters for resistance to hacking.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL6887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458854","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-21","<p>The radar control for F-35B Lightning II aircraft operates with all software versions, which continue to be developed. We remain on track to deliver our initial operating capability from land in 2018 and from our aircraft carriers in 2020.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-03-21T16:31:13.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458854/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458854/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the radar control for the UK’s F-35 Lightning II fighters operate using software version block 4, and whether it will be available in time for initial operating capability.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL6888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458855","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-17","<p>The UK's F-35B Lightning II aircraft will be able to communicate with all US variants of the F-35 and any other friendly forces on the same network.</p><p>The sensor suite on the F-35B Lightning II allows pilots to see a single integrated picture of the battlespace and automatically communicate and share that data with other strike aircraft, including the US F-35, as well as other airborne, surface and ground-based platforms.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-03-17T17:18:06.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458855/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458855/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the communications capability for the UK’s F-35 Lightning II fighters allows full integration with the 4C capability of US variants.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL6889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458856","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-17","<p>The F-35 fleet has now flown more than 50,000 hours (development test and production). This has included three periods of United States Marine Corps sea trials aboard the USS Wasp. The most recent of these was successfully concluded at the end of June 2015, within which the UK was fully integrated. Testing from UK aircraft carriers is due to start in 2018.</p><p>The UK programme remains on track to deliver initial operating capability from land in 2018 and aircraft carriers in 2020.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-03-17T17:17:55.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458856/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458856/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-09","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress is being made with the flight test programme for the UK’s F-35 Lightning II fighters.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL6890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458857","Department for Education","false","2016-03-16","<p>The aims of the research reported in<em> Factors associated with achievement: key stage 4,</em> were to assess the quality of the current measure of socio-economic deprivation used by the Department for Education and to identify potential alternative proxy indicators for deprivation.</p><p>The attached research brief and full report examines the relationship between attainment and household employment characteristics, including whether it is a single-parent household, and whether at least one parent was in full-time employment. This model was not included in the research brief because it was not considered a feasible alternative.</p><p> </p><p>The background characteristics used in the research were collected as part of the first wave of the Longitudinal Survey of Young People in England (LSYPE), which did not ask questions directly addressing the other factors mentioned. The research was exploratory, but also pragmatic, examining a broad range of measures but also mindful that not all measures would be available to the Department in the future. Measures such as domestic violence, alcohol addiction, drugs or parental mental health problems are not collected by the Department and were therefore not included in this analysis.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL6892","2016-03-16T13:10:12.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458857/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458857/answer","HL6891 and HL6892 - RR407_-_Factors_associated_with_achievement_-_key_stage_4.pdf ; HL6891 and HL6892 - RB407_-_Factors_associated_with_achievement_-_key_stage_4_brief.pdf","HL6891 and HL6892 - RR407_-_Factors_associated_with_achievement_-_key_stage_4.pdf ; HL6891 and HL6892 - RB407_-_Factors_associated_with_achievement_-_key_stage_4_brief.pdf","Full report - Factors Associated with Achievement ; Research brief","Full report - Factors Associated with Achievement ; Research brief","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458857/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Secondary Education: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the Department for Education's research brief, <i>Factors associated with achievement: key stage 4</i>, does not make any reference to the family structure in which the child is growing up, and in particular makes no distinction between a child being brought up by both parents living together and a child living in a single-parent family.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbourne",,"Lord Northbourne","HL6891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458858","Department for Education","false","2016-03-16","<p>The aims of the research reported in<em> Factors associated with achievement: key stage 4,</em> were to assess the quality of the current measure of socio-economic deprivation used by the Department for Education and to identify potential alternative proxy indicators for deprivation.</p><p>The attached research brief and full report examines the relationship between attainment and household employment characteristics, including whether it is a single-parent household, and whether at least one parent was in full-time employment. This model was not included in the research brief because it was not considered a feasible alternative.</p><p> </p><p>The background characteristics used in the research were collected as part of the first wave of the Longitudinal Survey of Young People in England (LSYPE), which did not ask questions directly addressing the other factors mentioned. The research was exploratory, but also pragmatic, examining a broad range of measures but also mindful that not all measures would be available to the Department in the future. Measures such as domestic violence, alcohol addiction, drugs or parental mental health problems are not collected by the Department and were therefore not included in this analysis.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL6891","2016-03-16T13:10:13.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458858/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458858/answer","HL6891 and HL6892 - RR407_-_Factors_associated_with_achievement_-_key_stage_4.pdf ; HL6891 and HL6892 - RB407_-_Factors_associated_with_achievement_-_key_stage_4_brief.pdf","HL6891 and HL6892 - RR407_-_Factors_associated_with_achievement_-_key_stage_4.pdf ; HL6891 and HL6892 - RB407_-_Factors_associated_with_achievement_-_key_stage_4_brief.pdf","Full report - Factors Associated with Achievement ; Research brief","Full report - Factors Associated with Achievement ; Research brief","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458858/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Secondary Education: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the Department for Education's research brief, <i>Factors associated with achievement: key stage 4</i>, does not mention whether they have considered the impact of domestic violence, alcohol addiction, drugs or parental mental health problems on children's lives.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbourne",,"Lord Northbourne","HL6892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458859","Department for Education","false","2016-03-21","<p>All schools should equip young people with the necessary knowledge and skills to leave school prepared for life in modern Britain. We are working to support schools to develop character traits like self-confidence, motivation and resilience in their students. These traits that can be developed in pupils of any age and in every school through the development of a positive culture and ethos, and supported by a rich provision of classroom and extra-curricular activities.</p><p>We have invested £5 million in character education, including £3.5 million of grants for 14 projects and £1 million to the Education Endowment Foundation to build evidence and expand research into the most effective character education. We will continue to support schools in developing the character of their pupils without prescribing compulsory measures. In order to do this, we will develop an online digital platform which will share evidence, innovation, and examples of best practice in character education. We will also promote character education to schools and organisations through a new round of character awards.</p><p>Of course, many schools and organisations are already supporting children to develop their character in and outside the classroom and through programmes such as the National Citizen Service (NCS). We will be investing over a billion pounds over the next four years to make NCS a rite of passage and to guarantee every child a place on NCS.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-03-21T16:34:07.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458859/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458859/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-09","Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to build self-confidence in children and young people in secondary schools, especially those who do not perform highly in academic subjects; and what assessment they have made of the impact of extra-curricular activities in building self-confidence and interpersonal skills.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbourne",,"Lord Northbourne","HL6893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458860","Attorney General","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Government Legal Department (GLD) conducts litigation for most government departments. GLD charges its government department clients for the litigation services it provides on an hourly fee basis. The Solicitor’s Office of HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) conduct litigation for HMRC.</p><p>(a) In the last 6 years there have been three cases where the Government has taken action against devolved administrations. The costs to the UK government in these cases was approximately £180,000.</p><p>(b) Neither GLD nor HMRC have centralised records that enable identification of the cost of litigation taken against Local Authorities. Carrying out a manual review of the stock of thousands of cases, would exceed the cost limit.</p><p>(c) Similarly, there is no central record which would enable the identification of cases against non – departmental public bodies.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-03-14T10:50:04.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458860/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458860/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-03-09","Attorney General: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the cost to the public purse of legal proceedings involving actions taken by the Government against (a) devolved administrations, (b) local government in England and (c) non-departmental public bodies has been in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","30454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458861","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-24","<p>Product safety legislation is in place to protect consumers, and is enforced by Trading Standards, who also enforce prohibitions against giving false information about products under the Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008. Where safety products bear a false trade mark, or deliberately copy a registered design, Trading Standards also have the ability to take enforcement action under intellectual property legislation.</p><p> </p><p>The Consumer Rights Act 2015 sets out the standards consumers can expect of the goods they obtain from traders and remedies if these rights are breached. The standards include the need for goods to be of satisfactory quality (including being fit for the purposes for which goods of that kind are usually supplied, being safe, and matching any description the goods were sold under), fit for a particular purpose (if that purpose was made known before sale), and as described . If these requirements are breached, consumers are entitled to reject the goods (if in the first 30 days), or require the trader to repair or replace the goods.</p><p> </p><p>Consumers can seek advice from the helpline run by Citizen’s Advice which offers a free service advising them on their rights and passes on details of complaints to Trading Standards where appropriate.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-24T15:32:52.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458861/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458861/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458861/answer/previousversion/51205","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Consumers: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that non-approved, sub-standard or fake safety products are not sold or passed on to the consumer.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","30467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458862","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Her Majesty’s Government is satisfied that we are not in breach of our international obligations. A licence will not be issued, to Saudi Arabia or any other destination, if to do so would be inconsistent with any provision of the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. On that basis there are no plans to commission a review of the legality of arms sales.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-21T15:23:47.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458862/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458862/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answers of 11 February and 2 March 2016 to Questions 27077 and 28765, if he will commission a review of the legality of arms sales to Saudi Arabia which takes account of all recent representations on that matter.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","30457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458863","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-17","<p>We have received no direct recent representations from the Union of Construction Allied Trades and Technicians. We continue to engage in discussions with the Industry Training Boards on the implications for the construction and engineering construction industry levies of the apprenticeship levy which will be introduced in April 2017.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-17T16:19:13.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458863/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458863/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Construction Industry Training Board: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent representations he has received from the Union of Construction Allied Trades and Technicians on the effect of proposed changes to the budget for training expertise of the Construction Industry Training Board on the future of the construction industry.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","30416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458864","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>The original industrial strategies did not contain estimates for employment by gender. Where sectors are clearly defined by Standard Industrial Classifications (SIC) we have been able to calculate estimates of these using published ONS data. Where this is not the case estimates are unavailable.</p><p><strong>Employment in Industrial Strategy Sectors by Gender 2014</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aerospace</p></td><td><p>99</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>113</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Automotive</p></td><td><p>131</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>148</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Construction (Contracting only)</p></td><td><p>1,833</p></td><td><p>283</p></td><td><p>2,116</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Digital Economy</p></td><td><p>1,071</p></td><td><p>475</p></td><td><p>1,546</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Life Sciences</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oil and Gas</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Professional and Business Services</p></td><td><p>2,439</p></td><td><p>1,812</p></td><td><p>4,251</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: BIS Calculations on ONS Annual Business Survey and Employee Jobs Data</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-16T16:43:11.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458864/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458864/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent estimate he has made of the number of (a) men and (b) women in each of the sectors covered by his Department's 11 industrial strategies.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","30420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458865","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-17","<p>Increasing exports, to all overseas markets, is a key factor in the Government’s long-term economic plan. Government departments are working together to support UK businesses looking to take advantage of overseas opportunities and to create a strong business environment that allows them to flourish both at home and overseas. A key part of this work is to identify export opportunities, many of which are based around the needs of high-growth and emerging markets.</p><p>This effort to drive economic growth is supported in part by my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister’s <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/trade-envoys" target="_blank">Trade Envoy Programme</a>, a group of appointed parliamentarians drawn from across the political spectrum. Envoys are carefully selected for their experience, skills and knowledge of particular sectors or markets, or their knowledge of business in an effort to identify substantial trade and investment opportunities. There are now 24 Trade Envoys covering 50 high-growth and emerging markets.</p><p>In addition, UK Trade and Investment is working on a joint international trade plan with Leeds City Region and other partners which will focus on key international markets, including high growth ones.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-17T16:19:53.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458865/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458865/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Trade Promotion: Leeds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to promote opportunities to access high growth markets abroad to businesses in the Leeds City Region.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","30397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458866","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-18","<p>It is already illegal to sell unsafe laser pens – generally defined as those over 1 milliwatt – to consumers in the UK. However, we are looking closely at a range of potential legislative options for controlling further the sales, use and possession of unsafe laser pens, especially in relation to children.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-18T14:07:55.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458866/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458866/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458866/answer/previousversion/52034","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Lasers: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what plans he has to regulate the power level of laser pens offered for sale in Britain.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","30477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458867","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>Salaries for special advisers appointed after the election have been set to reflect an individual’s role and responsibilities. As with other public servants, any future increases in special adviser salaries will be subject to the annual 1% cap for four years from 2016-17.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-15T09:45:41.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458867/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458867/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458867/answer/previousversion/51200","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-09","Cabinet Office and Treasury: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, who is responsible for authorising pay rises of more than one per cent in (a) his Department and (b) HM Treasury; and what procedure is followed when it is proposed to grant a pay rise of more than one per cent to an adviser.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","30455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458868","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-17","In February 2012, changes were announced to HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) tax dispute governance arrangements to provide greater assurance and transparency. One of the key changes was the appointment of a Tax Assurance Commissioner (TAC) who has an explicit challenge role in decision making on cases. The TAC plays no part in discussions with taxpayers on their tax liabilities and has no line management responsibilities for case-workers. In February 2015 the National Audit Office reported: “HMRC has responded effectively to our and the [Public Accounts] Committee’s criticism about the way it governs large tax disputes. The appointment of a tax assurance commissioner and the publication of his annual reports are welcome changes that have significantly improved public confidence in how HMRC deals with large companies.”","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-17T17:32:46.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458868/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458868/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure independent assurance of large tax settlements at HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","30442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458869","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-16","<p>No. The Compensation Code is based on the principle of equivalence, which says that the owner of the land taken should be paid neither less nor more than his loss. Paying compensation at more than market value would make public development more expensive and some schemes would become unviable. Offering such payments would not necessarily speed up negotiations or remove the need for compulsory purchase.</p><p>The Department issued guidance on the compulsory purchase process on the 29 October 2015 (web address: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/compulsory-purchase-process-and-the-crichel-down-rules-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/compulsory-purchase-process-and-the-crichel-down-rules-guidance</a> ) which encourages acquiring authorities to consider all of the costs involved in the compulsory purchase process when assessing the appropriate payments for purchase of land in advance of compulsory purchase.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-16T15:09:26.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458869/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458869/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Compulsory Purchase","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to offer compulsory purchase payments at 150 per cent of market value.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","30437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458870","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Government has been working closely with the mutual insurance industry and the financial regulators to inform the development of regulations to implement the Mutuals’ Deferred Shares Act. The Government expects to publish draft regulations for consultation in due course.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-14T15:23:34.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458870/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458870/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","Mutuals' Deferred Shares Act 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to consult on the draft Regulations to implement the Mutuals' Deferred Shares Act 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","30412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458871","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-16","<p>The Government’s Impact Assessment for the introduction of the National Living Wage estimates that the cost of increasing pay to the £7.20 rate on private sector and public sector employers will be approximately £800m and £36m respectively in 2016/17. The Government has not produced an estimate for each of the next three years.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-16T15:33:47.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458871/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458871/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-09","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the cost to (a) private and (b) public sector organisations of implementing the National Living Wage in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458872","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-15","<p>The impact on local authorities of the introduction of the National Living Wage was considered during the Spending Review as part of an overall assessment of spending pressures.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-15T12:06:39.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458872/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458872/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Local Government: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the (a) administrative and (b) staff cost to local authorities of implementing the National Living Wage in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458873","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-14","<p>HM Revenue Customs does hold this information. However, dealing with the request would exceed the cost limit under section 12(1) FOIA.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-14T15:28:50.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458873/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458873/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the total value of VAT arrears that had been owed for more than 12 months was recovered by HM Revenue and Customs in (a) Cardiff South and Penarth constituency, (b) Wales and (c) the UK in last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","30450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458874","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-17","<p>The 2011 Green Paper “A state pension for the 21st century” set out the Government’s vision for a simpler state pension and proposed the new State Pension should start from April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The 2013 White Paper “The single-tier pension: a simple foundation for saving” which set out proposals for the new State Pension in more detail proposed that it should be introduced in April 2017 at the earliest. However, having noted the positive responses to the White Paper, the Government looked again at whether it would be possible to introduce the reform earlier.</p><p> </p><p>The Government decided to return to the original timetable to deliver the reform as soon as possible, to support the roll-out of automatic enrolment and provide certainty concerning the changes for both individuals and their pension schemes at the earliest opportunity. The decision to return to the original implementation date also meant that around 400,000 more people would reach State Pension age under the new State Pension, including every woman affected by State Pension age changes in the Pensions Act 2011.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-17T14:44:22.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458874/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458874/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-09","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what factors he took into account when setting the new state pension age cut-off date.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","30391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458875","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-17","<p>The government set out its plans for funding for local roads and bus services in England, in the Spending Review 2015. Funding for these matters is devolved in Scotland.</p><p> </p><p>The government is providing nearly £5 billion of funding for local roads maintenance in England during this Spending Review period, a £300 million increase compared to the previous Parliament. This is in addition to a planned £15 billion upgrade to England’s motorways and major A roads, the largest investment in a generation.</p><p> </p><p>On buses, the government provided £250 million last year to bus operators in England through the Bus Service Operators Grant, and has committed to continue providing this support. And we remain committed to funding almost £1 billion of local authority spending on the concessionary travel entitlement every year.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-17T13:17:36.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458875/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458875/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-09","Transport: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will increase funding for local roads and Government support for local bus services.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","30482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458876","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-15","<p>The most recent published statistics on fixed penalty notices issued by Local Authorities for nuisance parking cover 2006 to 2009 and are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/dataset/fixed-penalty-notice-nuisance-parking" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/dataset/fixed-penalty-notice-nuisance-parking</a></p><p> </p><p>According to this data:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2006/07</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2007/08</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008/09</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of Fixed Penalties Issued</strong></p></td><td><p>1657</p></td><td><p>74</p></td><td><p>150</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The data does not specify how many cases were successfully appealed. The data includes the number of fixed penalty notices which were:</p><p> </p><ul><li>cancelled;</li><li>taken to court following non-payment; and</li><li>not paid and on which no further action was taken.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p>“Nuisance parking” includes the two offences of (i) exposing or advertising for sale as part of a business two or more vehicles parked on a road; and (ii) repairing a vehicle parked on the road, either as part of business or in a way that gives reasonable cause for annoyance to people nearby.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-03-15T11:39:39.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458876/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458876/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-09","Motor Vehicles: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people have been charged under the Clean Neighbourhoods and Environment Act 2005 for selling private vehicles on public roads; and how many such cases were successfully appealed.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","30441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458877","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-14","<p>DCLG have provided grant funding to 45 bodies under the Charities Act during the financial year 2015/2016. The anti-lobbying clause is a standard clause in all of the Department's grant funding agreements and therefore applies to all 45 recipients.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-14T16:22:47.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458877/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458877/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-09","Department for Communities and Local Government: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which charities have received grant funding from his Department since the introduction of the anti-lobbying clause.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","30411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458878","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-14","<p>The Government’s recently published ‘Sport Strategy’ (https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/486622/Sporting_Future_ACCESSIBLE.pdf) sets out plans for all children to benefit from participating in sport - regardless of their background or socioeconomic status.</p><p> </p><p>Through the new strategy, for the first time Sport England will invest in sporting provision for children aged five and over - previously the starting age was 14 years old.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-14T14:21:59.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458878/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458878/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","Sports: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to increase access to sporting activities for children in low income households.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","30417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458879","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-16","<p>We have not identified any Official Development Assistance monies spent to date by the Department under the powers provided by the International Development Act 2002.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-16T12:25:04.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458879/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458879/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 29 February 2016 to Question 28855, how much of that spending in each of the last three years is subject to the provisions of the International Development Act 2002.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","30421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458880","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-14","<p>Several elements of the 2012 warm-up track have been used in various athletics venues around the country including Gateshead International Stadium, Birmingham Alexander Stadium, Lee Valley Stadium, Allianz Stadium and Swansea Stadium.</p><p> </p><p>The E20 Stadium Partnership (a partnership between the London Borough of Newham and London Legacy Development Corporation, which manages the stadium on Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park) is working with organisations, including the London Marathon Charitable Trust (which has funded the future community track at the stadium), to identify uses for the remainder of the London 2012 warm-up track.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-14T14:42:22.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458880/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458880/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","Olympic Games 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, who is responsible for the future of the London 2012 athletics warm-up track.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","30439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458881","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-14","<p>Based on DCMS modelled estimates and current delivery plans, it is estimated that 99.7% of premises in the Northampton South constituency will have access to superfast broadband by December 2017. Additional funding sources, including Northamptonshire’s share of the £129 million of early gainshare funding that BT will return in response to the high levels of take-up being achieved, will allow coverage to be extended further in Northampton South and the rest of the area covered by the Northamptonshire broadband project.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government's intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation will give people the legal right to request a broadband connection, no matter where they live, by the end of this Parliament. Our ambition is that this should be set at 10 Mbps.</p><p>Current estimates suggest that almost 90% of premises in the Northampton South constituency are subject to commercial rollout, and a further 2,739 premises now have coverage as a result of this Government's superfast broadband programme.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-14T15:12:02.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458881/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458881/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-09","Broadband: Northampton South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the extent of the rollout of super-fast broadband in the Northampton South constituency.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","30395"
